5.1 14.8/12.1 4.1/7.7 2.4/4.8 28.3/25.3 19.4/14.4 8.7/6.8 5.5/3.8 whisper-large-v3 20.4/27.5 15.6/19.5 15.6/11.9 11.8/8.7 3.2/6.3 1.7/4.0 10.5/8.3 8.7/5.5 11.0/8.6 7.8/6.1 whisper-large-v3-turbo 16.0/23.7 12.0/16.5 15.3/11.9 11.5/9.0 3.1/6.3 1.7/3.9 9.9/8.1 8.5/5.2 13.3/11.1 9.8/7.9 whisper-medium.en 20.1/25.1 15.3/18.0 21.2/16.1 16.6/13.2 4.0/7.7 2.2/5.0 17.3/14.6 18.3/14.2 9.0/7.2 5.6/3.2 whisper-small.en 21.2/25.1 16.5/18.0 18.2/14.1 13.9/10.9 3.9/7.5 2.1/4.6 10.6/8.3 15.6/12.0 9.5/8.1 5.9/3.4 whisper-tiny 30.1/31.9 21.7/21.5 24.0/20.3 17.5/14.4 8.1/11.9 3.9/6.7 17.6/15.3 13.0/9.5 13.2/11.2 7.4/6.3 Table 14: Actual and approximated WER and CER, separated by a forward slash, across five standard datasets. The regression model is trained on nine datasets and tested on one, with this process repeated for all datasets, ensuring that the test data is always out-of-distribution.\n23146"}, {"url": "https://arxiv.org/html/2306.12577", "title": "NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech ...", "content": "This paper introduces NoRefER, a novel referenceless quality metric for automatic speech recognition (ASR) systems. Traditional reference-based metrics for evaluating ASR systems require costly ground-truth transcripts. NoRefER overcomes this limitation by fine-tuning a multilingual language model for pair-wise ranking ASR hypotheses using contrastive learning with Siamese network architecture. The self-supervised NoRefER exploits the known quality relationships between hypotheses from multiple compression levels of an ASR for learning to rank intra-sample hypotheses by quality, which is essential for model comparisons. The semi-supervised version also uses a referenced dataset to improve its inter-sample quality ranking, which is crucial for selecting potentially erroneous samples. The [...] self-supervised parallel ASR hypothesis pairs in total, of which 20% were reserved as a validation-set for early-stopping. An additional batch of data from the Common Voice training dataset was used to facilitate semi-supervised training. This batch included 148,393 unique hypotheses transcribed with top commercial ASR(s), and their WER was calculated to evaluate the transcription quality. The trained referenceless metric was blind-tested on multiple speech datasets, including Common Voice (English, French, Spanish) , Libri-Speech (English) , and a proprietary dataset containing 11 hours of meetings in-between non-native English speakers. The transcription hypotheses were obtained from top commercial ASR engines, namely AWS, AppTek, Azure, Deepgram, Google, and OpenAI's Whisper-Large, for [...] where α𝛼\\alphaitalic\\_α is a weight parameter for combining the two losses and was set to 0.5 by default. The supervised and self-supervised mini-batches are equal and set to 128 during the training. This semi-supervised training enables NoRefER to learn from a large amount of self-supervised and a limited amount of supervised information, leading to improved performance on the referenceless ASR quality estimation. Combining the self-supervised and supervised information enables the model to generalize better to unseen data, resulting in a more robust and accurate referenceless ASR quality metric. This is particularly useful for comparing non-parallel hypotheses, e.g. when prioritizing production hypotheses for post-editing in active-learning while extending the ASR corpus to get the most", "score": 0.57780564, "raw_content": "Kamer Ali Yuksel,\nThiago Ferreira,\nGolara Javadi,\nMohamed El-Badrashiny,\nAhmet Gunduz\n\n# NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\n\n###### Abstract\n\nThis paper introduces NoRefER, a novel referenceless quality metric for automatic speech recognition (ASR) systems. Traditional reference-based metrics for evaluating ASR systems require costly ground-truth transcripts. NoRefER overcomes this limitation by fine-tuning a multilingual language model for pair-wise ranking ASR hypotheses using contrastive learning with Siamese network architecture. The self-supervised NoRefER exploits the known quality relationships between hypotheses from multiple compression levels of an ASR for learning to rank intra-sample hypotheses by quality, which is essential for model comparisons. The semi-supervised version also uses a referenced dataset to improve its inter-sample quality ranking, which is crucial for selecting potentially erroneous samples. The results indicate that NoRefER correlates highly with reference-based metrics and their intra-sample ranks, indicating a high potential for referenceless ASR evaluation or a/b testing.\n\nIndex Terms: Speech Recognition, Referenceless ASR Quality Estimation, Semi-Supervised Learning, Contrastive-Learning\n\n## 1 Introduction\n\nAutomatic Speech Recognition (ASR) is considered to be the future means of communication between humans and machines. This field has made significant progress over the last few years with the advent of Deep Neural Networks [[1](#bib.bib1), [2](#bib.bib2)]. Modern ASR systems rely on large amounts of annotated speech to learn accurate speech representation and recognition, and they can achieve remarkable accuracy for resource-rich languages like English. The performance of ASR systems usually depends on two factors, the accuracy of the output produced as well as the processing speed of the ASR. The most commonly used evaluation metric for ASR systems is Word-Error-Rate (WER), which calculates errors on the word level and requires annotated resources as ground-truth transcripts that may not always be available or accurately reflect the ASR output's quality.\n\nASR quality estimation without transcripts follows a two-stage framework, including feature extraction and WER prediction. Most of the research in this field used hand-crafted features to build linear regression-based algorithms [[3](#bib.bib3)]. NoRefER, a novel referenceless quality metric for ASR systems, is introduced in this paper to reduce the necessity of manual processes, and to present a measure for evaluating ASR performance with limited or no ground-truth references. The NoRefER referenceless quality metric provides a much-needed solution to the limitations of traditional reference-based metrics through fine-tuning a multi-language language model (LM) with contrastive learning and pair-wise ranking (Fig. [1](#S1.F1 \"Figure 1 ‣ 1 Introduction ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\")). First, a referenceless training dataset of ASR hypothesis pairs is formed from the pairwise combinations of unique outputs of OpenAI’s Whisper ASR model [[4](#bib.bib4)] with six different compression levels. The higher the compression level gets, the lower the quality is expected. This dataset is used for self-supervised contrastive learning using a Siamese architecture [[5](#bib.bib5)]. Then, The fine-tuned LM is used as a shared backbone with the supervised task on a referenced dataset. The two pairwise ranking branches are used to improve the performance of the proposed metric for inter and intra-sample ranking by leveraging both datasets. The intra-sample and inter-sample pair-wise quality ranking decisions of the referenceless metric are validated on several blind test datasets in various languages in comparison with the perplexity metric from XLM-RoBERTa-Large [[6](#bib.bib6)]. All models and source-codes required for reproducing the experimental results are available here: <https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Interspeech-NoRefER-6887>\n\nThe contributions from this paper can be listed as the followings: i) a novel method for self-supervision of the ASR hypothesis quality by utilizing multiple compression levels of an ASR model; ii) a multi-language referenceless ASR quality estimation metric through an LM fine-tuned with contrastive learning using a Siamese network architecture and pair-wise ranking; iii) applying semi-supervised learning to improve the self-supervised metric's performance on inter-sample ranking by using two corpora with and without reference transcriptions; iv) demonstrating the significant potential of the proposed metric against the perplexity from the state-of-art multi-lingual LM, regarding their correlation with WER scores and ranks.\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/2306.12577v1/figs/framework1.png)\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/2306.12577v1/figs/framework1.png)\n\n## 2 Related Work\n\nReference-based evaluation metrics are among the most widely used methods to evaluate the performance of ASR systems. The most common metrics are WER and phoneme error rate (PER). WER measures the proportion of words in the reference that are not recognized correctly, whereas PER measures the proportion of phonemes that are not recognized correctly [[7](#bib.bib7)]. Both metrics require a ground-truth reference transcript to compare the ASR(s) outputs. Their main limitation is the dependence on the existence of a reference transcript, where a poor reference can also negatively affect the accuracy of the evaluation.\n\nReferenceless evaluation metrics for ASR do not rely on a ground-truth reference. Some existing referenceless evaluation metrics include confidence scores and confidence-based fusion [[8](#bib.bib8), [9](#bib.bib9), [10](#bib.bib10)]. Confidence scores are usually generated by the ASR system and are used to rank alternative hypotheses. These scores are not practical for the black-box ASR systems unless the model is designed to output the confidence score. The confidence-based fusion combines multiple outputs from different ASR systems to produce a single output with improved quality. However, they are dependent on the particular ASR system being used and cannot capture the full context of the ASR output; and therefore, they may not be accurate in some instances.\n\nPrevious research on ASR quality estimation has mainly focused on supervised regression or ordinal classification of speech and language features [[11](#bib.bib11), [9](#bib.bib9), [12](#bib.bib12), [8](#bib.bib8)]. For example, [[3](#bib.bib3)] used a bidirectional transformer language model to estimate ASR quality by modeling the empirical distribution of WER through a neural zero-inflated Beta regression layer. Ali and Renals [[13](#bib.bib13)] who did not have access to the ASR system, utilized a multistream end-to-end architecture with acoustic, lexical, and phonotactic features to estimate WER. Sheshadri et al. [[14](#bib.bib14)] proposed a BERT-based architecture with speech features for balanced ordinal classification to estimate WER. However, none of these referenceless ASR quality estimators were solely based on language features and were not trained with references. On the other hand, Namazifar et al. [[15](#bib.bib15)] leveraged the robustness of warped language models against transcription noise to correct the transcriptions of spoken language, which resulted in a 10% reduction in WER for both automatic and manual transcriptions. While they could use the distance with improved transcription for ASR quality estimation, they did not study that use-case.\n\nLastly, the WMT Quality Estimation Shared Task [[16](#bib.bib16)] is a well-known evaluation framework for quality estimation (QE) metrics in machine translation (MT). The task recently also includes ranking the quality of machine-generated translations without access to reference translations. This is done by training quality estimation models on parallel sentences with human-annotated quality scores. As an outcome of the WMT Shared Task, various referenceless QE metrics have emerged in the MT domain, including COMET-QE [[17](#bib.bib17)]. COMET-QE also utilizes contrastive-learning to fine-tune a pre-trained multi-lingual LM for MT quality estimation to distinguish between high and low-quality parallel MT hypotheses. However, the fine-tuning of COMET-QE relies on and is limited by the existence of a human-evaluation dataset or ground-truth references. Whereas, in this work, self-supervision in contrastive-learning is achieved via exploiting the known quality relationships without costly human annotations to compose a training dataset for the metric.\n\n## 3 Methodology\n\nThe proposed method utilizes a pre-trained language model that is fine-tuned using contrastive learning, employing a Siamese network architecture for pair-wise quality ranking decisions. To achieve this, multi-task learning is utilized, with a shared backbone that processes unique pair combinations from two sets of datasets for training and validation. The first task focuses on self-supervised learning by exploiting known quality relationships between multiple compression levels of an ASR model. The second task employs supervised learning for inter-sample comparison, utilizing a dataset with ground-truth. By multi-tasking self-supervised and supervised learning, the proposed method offers a semi-supervised approach to train a LM for the quality ranking of the intra- and inter-sample hypotheses.\n\n### 3.1 Dataset generation\n\nTo train and validate the proposed referenceless quality metric with self-supervision, unique outputs from an ASR model [[4](#bib.bib4)] are utilized to form pairwise combinations that can be used for contrastive-learning. Multiple compression levels are used as a proxy for quality, where higher model compression levels indicates lower-quality transcriptions. The process of extracting unique pairs involves selecting two ASR hypotheses, one with higher quality and one with lower quality, for the same speech and combining them into a single pair. These pairs are shuffled and placed into mini-batches for training and validation sets. Inconsistent pairs, for which the exact reverse pair also exists, are dropped. Each pair's training and validation loss is weighted using the Word Error Rate (WER) between the paired hypotheses. The model is penalized more for incorrect pair-wise ranking decisions when the distance between two hypotheses is high, as it is more acceptable to make a pair-wise ranking mistake when they are close. By fine-tuning the proposed Siamese network using this approach, the quality metric can be trained and validated effectively without requiring ground-truth transcriptions.\n\n### 3.2 Self-supervised learning\n\nThe proposed method utilizes a pre-trained cross-lingual language model (LM) with a Siamese network architecture, followed by a dense encoder that reduces the embeddings produced by the LM to a single scalar logit. This logit is then used to compare the outputs of the Siamese network. The pre-trained LM in this architecture is MiniLMv2, a smaller and (2.7x) faster language understanding model with 117M parameters distilled from XLM-RoBERTa-Large [[18](#bib.bib18)], which has 560M parameters. The dense encoder has two linear layers with a 10% dropout ratio and a non-linear activation function in-between.\n\nTo fine-tune the pre-trained LM on a pair-wise ranking task with contrastive learning, a self-supervised learning method that trains a model to distinguish between positive and negative examples, the proposed method utilizes ASR outputs to generate pairs that can be compared to predict the one with higher quality. The contrastive-learning process uses the shared network to take a pair as input and output a logit for each. These logits are then subtracted from each other, and a Sigmoid activation function is applied to their difference to produce a probability for binary classification of their qualities. The Adafactor [[19](#bib.bib19)] optimizer is used with its default parameters and a learning rate of 1e-5 for fine-tuning the LM on this pair-wise ranking task using Binary Cross-Entropy (Log-Loss) weighted by the WER in-between pairs. Eq. [1](#S3.E1 \"1 ‣ 3.2 Self-supervised learning ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\") shows the self-supervised loss.\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | ℒs⁢e⁢l⁢f=−1N⁢∑i=1N𝒲⁢(Pi)⁢log⁡(σ⁢(ℳ⁢(Pi+)−ℳ⁢(Pi−)))subscriptℒ𝑠𝑒𝑙𝑓1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑁𝒲subscript𝑃𝑖𝜎ℳsubscript𝑃subscript𝑖ℳsubscript𝑃subscript𝑖\\displaystyle\\mathcal{L}\\_{self}=-\\frac{1}{N}\\sum\\_{i=1}^{N}\\mathcal{W}(P\\_{i})% \\log(\\sigma(\\mathcal{M}(P\\_{i\\_{+}})-\\mathcal{M}(P\\_{i\\_{-}})))caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_s italic\\_e italic\\_l italic\\_f end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT = - divide start\\_ARG 1 end\\_ARG start\\_ARG italic\\_N end\\_ARG ∑ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i = 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT caligraphic\\_W ( italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) roman\\_log ( italic\\_σ ( caligraphic\\_M ( italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) - caligraphic\\_M ( italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT - end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ) ) |  | (1) |\n\nwhere 𝒲(.)\\mathcal{W}(.)caligraphic\\_W ( . ) is the WER in-between pairs, σ(.)\\sigma(.)italic\\_σ ( . ) is the Sigmoid activation, ℳ(.)\\mathcal{M}(.)caligraphic\\_M ( . ) is the output of the model. N is the number of pairs, and Pi+subscript𝑃subscript𝑖P\\_{i\\_{+}}italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT and Pi−subscript𝑃subscript𝑖P\\_{i\\_{-}}italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT - end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT show the positive and negative samples of each pair, respectively. By utilizing this contrastive-learning process, the LM can learn a high-level representation of pairs that is discriminative of their quality. This approach can effectively train a referenceless quality metric, allowing accurate intra-sample hypothesis comparisons without references.\n\n### 3.3 Semi-supervised learning\n\nThe NoRefER method extends its self-supervised fine-tuning to a semi-supervised version by introducing an additional Log-Loss term (Fig. [1](#S1.F1 \"Figure 1 ‣ 1 Introduction ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\")). The supervised batch of pairs used for this task includes pairwise combinations of inter-sample hypotheses for non-parallel speech samples, where the quality relationship and the reference are known and can be quantified using reference-based ASR quality metrics (such as WER). In contrast to the self-supervised loss term, the losses of the supervised pairs are not weighted by the distance between hypotheses but by the positive-class weight of randomly formed pairs. To maximize the efficiency of the limited supervised hypotheses, the pairwise combinations of inter-sample hypotheses are formed by self-concatenating each mini-batch of supervised hypotheses, shuffling the concatenated column, and re-assigning the pairwise ranking binary classification labels based on the WERs calculated from ground-truth references. This approach randomizes the formation of pairwise combinations of supervised inter-sample hypotheses during the training process. With this framework, the training loss is comprised of two objectives: the self-supervised loss (ℒs⁢e⁢l⁢fsubscriptℒ𝑠𝑒𝑙𝑓\\mathcal{L}\\_{self}caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_s italic\\_e italic\\_l italic\\_f end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT) on a generated referenceless dataset, and the supervised loss (ℒs⁢u⁢psubscriptℒ𝑠𝑢𝑝\\mathcal{L}\\_{sup}caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_s italic\\_u italic\\_p end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT) on supervised hypotheses. Eq. [2](#S3.E2 \"2 ‣ 3.3 Semi-supervised learning ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\") shows the supervised loss, and Eq. [3](#S3.E3 \"3 ‣ 3.3 Semi-supervised learning ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\") shows the sum of both losses for multi-tasking in semi-supervised learning.\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | ℒs⁢u⁢p=−1N⁢∑i=1Nlog⁡(σ⁢(ℳ⁢(Pi+)−ℳ⁢(Pi−)))subscriptℒ𝑠𝑢𝑝1𝑁superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑁𝜎ℳsubscript𝑃subscript𝑖ℳsubscript𝑃subscript𝑖\\displaystyle\\mathcal{L}\\_{sup}=-\\frac{1}{N}\\sum\\_{i=1}^{N}\\log(\\sigma(\\mathcal{% M}(P\\_{i\\_{+}})-\\mathcal{M}(P\\_{i\\_{-}})))caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_s italic\\_u italic\\_p end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT = - divide start\\_ARG 1 end\\_ARG start\\_ARG italic\\_N end\\_ARG ∑ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i = 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic\\_N end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman\\_log ( italic\\_σ ( caligraphic\\_M ( italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) - caligraphic\\_M ( italic\\_P start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT - end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ) ) |  | (2) |\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | ℒS⁢E⁢M⁢I=α⁢ℒs⁢u⁢p+(1−α)⁢ℒs⁢e⁢l⁢fsubscriptℒ𝑆𝐸𝑀𝐼𝛼subscriptℒ𝑠𝑢𝑝1𝛼subscriptℒ𝑠𝑒𝑙𝑓\\displaystyle\\mathcal{L}\\_{SEMI}=\\alpha\\mathcal{L}\\_{sup}+(1-\\alpha)\\mathcal{L}\\_% {self}caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_S italic\\_E italic\\_M italic\\_I end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic\\_α caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_s italic\\_u italic\\_p end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + ( 1 - italic\\_α ) caligraphic\\_L start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_s italic\\_e italic\\_l italic\\_f end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT |  | (3) |\n\nwhere α𝛼\\alphaitalic\\_α is a weight parameter for combining the two losses and was set to 0.5 by default. The supervised and self-supervised mini-batches are equal and set to 128 during the training. This semi-supervised training enables NoRefER to learn from a large amount of self-supervised and a limited amount of supervised information, leading to improved performance on the referenceless ASR quality estimation. Combining the self-supervised and supervised information enables the model to generalize better to unseen data, resulting in a more robust and accurate referenceless ASR quality metric. This is particularly useful for comparing non-parallel hypotheses, e.g. when prioritizing production hypotheses for post-editing in active-learning while extending the ASR corpus to get the most improvement from fine-tuning.\n\n## 4 Experiments\n\nIn this section, the experimental settings and results are presented. All experiments were performed on a desktop computer running 64-bit Ubuntu 22.04 LTS. The computer was equipped with an AMD Ryzen 5900X CPU and 64GB of memory, and an Nvidia GeForce RTX 3090 GPU with 24GB of GPU memory. Due to the use of a pre-trained LM, the hyperparameters of the architecture were fixed except for the hidden-layer size (32) and the drop-out ratio (10%) of the dense encoder, which are set manually without an extensive hyper-parameter search. The Adafactor optimizer is also used with its default parameters and 1e-5 learning-rate suggested for fine-tuning MiniLMv2 [[18](#bib.bib18)].\n\nThe referenceless metric was trained using a large self-supervised corpus incorporating unique transcription hypotheses from OpenAI's Whisper ASR model [[4](#bib.bib4)] for each audio sample available at CMU MOSEI and MOSEAS datasets [[20](#bib.bib20), [21](#bib.bib21)]. This corpus consisted of 134 hours of speech from YouTube videos spoken by 2,645 individuals. Almost half of the speeches in this corpus were in English, while the remaining duration was distributed uniformly among French, Spanish, Portuguese, and German languages. The proposed metric was self-supervised using unique pairs of speech transcripts, with one hypothesis in each pair known to have a higher quality than the other based on the compression level. After removing inconsistent pairs, there were 800,340 self-supervised parallel ASR hypothesis pairs in total, of which 20% were reserved as a validation-set for early-stopping. An additional batch of data from the Common Voice training dataset was used to facilitate semi-supervised training. This batch included 148,393 unique hypotheses transcribed with top commercial ASR(s), and their WER was calculated to evaluate the transcription quality. The trained referenceless metric was blind-tested on multiple speech datasets, including Common Voice (English, French, Spanish) [[22](#bib.bib22)], Libri-Speech (English) [[23](#bib.bib23)], and a proprietary dataset containing 11 hours of meetings in-between non-native English speakers. The transcription hypotheses were obtained from top commercial ASR engines, namely AWS, AppTek, Azure, Deepgram, Google, and OpenAI's Whisper-Large, for each speech segment in them.\n\n| Test Dataset - Language | Model | Correlation with WER ranking | | | Correlations with WER score itself | | |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Pearson | Spearman | Kendall | Pearson | Spearman | Kendall |\n| Common Voice Test - English | NoRefER-Self | 0.56 | 0.48 | 0.55 | 0.42 | 0.33 | 0.24 |\n| NoRefER-Semi | 0.53 | 0.44 | 0.52 | 0.48 | 0.53 | 0.40 |\n|  | XLMR-Large | 0.26 | 0.22 | 0.26 | 0.02 | 0.21 | 0.15 |\n| Common Voice Test - French | NoRefER-Self | 0.48 | 0.40 | 0.48 | 0.38 | 0.33 | 0.24 |\n| NoRefER-Semi | 0.48 | 0.39 | 0.48 | 0.50 | 0.56 | 0.41 |\n|  | XLMR-Large | 0.20 | 0.17 | 0.20 | 0.02 | 0.20 | 0.14 |\n| Common Voice Test - Spanish | NoRefER-Self | 0.58 | 0.52 | 0.58 | 0.49 | 0.40 | 0.30 |\n| NoRefER-Semi | 0.56 | 0.48 | 0.55 | 0.53 | 0.45 | 0.34 |\n|  | XLMR-Large | 0.25 | 0.22 | 0.25 | -0.01 | 0.20 | 0.14 |\n| Libri-Speech Test Clean - Eng. | NoRefER-Self | 0.42 | 0.35 | 0.42 | 0.30 | 0.13 | 0.09 |\n| NoRefER-Semi | 0.57 | 0.47 | 0.56 | 0.42 | 0.51 | 0.37 |\n|  | XLMR-Large | 0.22 | 0.17 | 0.21 | -0.06 | 0.13 | 0.09 |\n| Proprietary - Non-Native Eng. | NoRefER-Self | 0.37 | 0.31 | 0.37 | 0.10 | 0.33 | 0.22 |\n| NoRefER-Semi | 0.38 | 0.32 | 0.38 | 0.16 | 0.44 | 0.31 |\n|  | XLMR-Large | 0.29 | 0.25 | 0.30 | -0.02 | -0.02 | -0.01 |\n\nAs a baseline, the referenceless metric was compared with the perplexity metric obtained from the state-of-the-art multilingual LM, XLM-RoBERTa Large [[6](#bib.bib6)]. The perplexity metric measures the average number of predictions a language model must make to generate a speech transcript. A lower perplexity indicates a higher quality speech transcript, suggesting that the language model is more confident in its predictions. Table [1](#S4.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\") compares the proposed referenceless metric with the perplexity metric on different datasets and languages; where it consistently outperformed the baseline in all the blind test datasets, demonstrating its superiority in estimating ASR output quality. The table presents various correlation coefficients obtained by the proposed referenceless metric with the actual WER ranks and scores in datasets from multiple languages. The Pearson correlation coefficient measures the linear relationship between two variables, the Spearman correlation coefficient is a non-parametric measure of the monotonic relationship between two variables, and the Kendall correlation coefficient measures the agreement between two rankings and is non-parametric. For all correlation coefficients, the scores range from -1 to 1, with -1 indicating a strong negative correlation, 0 indicating no correlation, and 1 indicating a strong positive correlation [[24](#bib.bib24)]. The default SciPy [[25](#bib.bib25)] implementations is used for their calculation.\n\nIn the ablation study, the performance of NoRefER was compared using two different training methods. Firstly, NoRefER was trained using only self-supervised learning on a referenceless dataset of pairs, as described in Section [3.1](#S3.SS1 \"3.1 Dataset generation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\") (NoRefER-Self). Secondly, NoRefER was trained using the multi-tasked semi-supervised learning approach proposed (NoRefER-Semi). As shown in Table [1](#S4.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ NoRefER: a Referenceless Quality Metric for Automatic Speech Recognition via Semi-Supervised Language Model Fine-Tuning with Contrastive Learning\"), the study results indicated a strong correlation between the two techniques. However, the NoRefER-Self model had limitations regarding inter-sample comparisons, as it showed weaker correlations with WER scores. In contrast, the NoRefER-Semi model had less correlation with WER ranking and was dependent on supervised data. The self-supervised NoRefER model was fine-tuned in 26 minutes and 47 seconds, while the semi-supervised version took 59 minutes and 16 seconds. The experiments measured an average duration of 0.095 seconds model inference time per hypothesis sample, which was the same for the both Self and Semi versions of NoRefER.\n\nThe pre-trained NoRefER weights and architecture, and the Python scripts required for reproducing all experimental results are open-sourced at this repository: <https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Interspeech-NoRefER-6887>\n\n## 5 Discussion\n\nThe experimental results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed referenceless quality metric and its potential impact in the ASR field. The evaluation of the referenceless metric revealed a strong correlation with the uncased and unpunctuated WER ranks and scores of the top commercial engines across samples. The high correlation with WER scores and ranks indicates the inter-sample and intra-sample reliability of the referenceless metric, respectively. When the contrastive learning is only performed between intra-sample hypotheses via self-supervision, NoRefER-Self achieves lower correlations with WER ranks than WER scores. In contrast, NoRefER-Semi also correlates well with WER scores due to the supervised inter-sample pairs used in its training. The experimental findings demonstrate that the referenceless metric can provide meaningful quality comparisons between different ASR models, serving as a viable alternative evaluation metric for ASR systems. Moreover, these results confirm the applicability of the referenceless metric over reference-based ones when comparing or A/B testing multiple ASR models/versions on production samples (for which ground-truth references are often not available) and selecting challenging ones for debugging and post-editing.\n\n## 6 Conclusion\n\nThis work proposes a multi-lingual referenceless quality metric for ASR systems, which is useful when no ground truth is available to evaluate the quality of ASR outputs. The approach uses a pre-trained language model (MiniLMv2), fine-tuned on two datasets of varying quality using contrastive learning and pair-wise ranking. The results of the experiments demonstrate that the referenceless metric outperforms traditional reference-based and perplexity metrics from pre-trained language models. In addition, when tested on a blind dataset containing outputs from commercial ASR engines, the referenceless metric exhibits a strong correlation with the WER scores and ranks of these engines. This referenceless metric has the potential to significantly enhance the improvement and evaluation lifecycle of ASR systems in real-world applications. The future-research can focus on transfer-learning the proposed metric by incorporating audio-based features for referenceless quality estimation.\n\n## References\n\n![[LOGO]](data:image/png;base64,)"}, {"url": "https://www.isca-archive.org/interspeech_2024/kim24t_interspeech.pdf", "title": "[PDF] Self-training ASR Guided by Unsupervised ASR Teacher", "content": "2. Backgrounds 2.1. Self-supervised Learning: Data2vec2 Data2vec2 trains a transformer encoder with a self-distillation strategy, in which a student and teacher are kept updated. The student takes speech X as an input and converts to latent speech representation Z = [z1, z2, · · · , zT ] by a multi-layer convolu-tional encoder where T is the number of speech frames. The latent representation Z is randomly masked and fed to the trans-former layer to learn local and global relationships among the speech frames by self-attention algorithm, which outputs a con-Interspeech 2024 1-5 September 2024, Kos, Greece 2865 10.21437/Interspeech.2024-2323 text representation C = [c1, c2, · · · , cT ]. In order to predict a pseudo-target yt on the masked frames, a final decoder projects the context [...] 4. Experimental Settings 4.1. Database We used the LibriSpeech (LS) dataset for unsupervised pre-training, specifically the LS 960 hours including train-clean-100, train-clean-360, and train-other-500. For supervised fine-tuning, we used the LS 100 hours (train-clean-100). We vali-dated the models on LS development sets (dev-clean, dev-other) and evaluated them on LS test sets (test-clean, test-other). [...] C. Wang, Y. Wang, Y. Wu, S. Chen, J. Li, S. Liu, and F. Wei, “Supervision-guided codebooks for masked prediction in speech pre-training.” in Proc. Interspeech, 2022, pp. 6224–6228.\n C. K. Yeh, J. Chen, C. Yu, and D. Yu, “Unsupervised speech recognition via segmental empiricaloutput distribution matching.” in Proc. ICLR., 2019.\n K. Y. Chen, C. P. Tsai, D. R. Liu, H. Y. Lee, and S. Lee, “Com-pletely unsupervised speechrecognition by a generative adversar-ial network harmonized with iteratively refined hidden markov-models.” in Proc. Interspeech, 2019.\n D. Gao, J. Shi, S. P. Chuang, L. P. Garcia, H.-Y. Lee, S. Watanabe, and S. Khudanpur, “Euro: Espnet unsupervised asr open-source toolkit.” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.", "score": 0.46964246, "raw_content": "Self-training ASR Guided by Unsupervised ASR Teacher Hyung Yong Kim1, Byeong-Yeol Kim1, Yunkyu Lim1, Jihwan Park1, Shukjae Choi1, Yooncheol Ju1, Jinseok Park1, Youshin Lim1, Seung Woo Yu1, Hanbin Lee1, Shinji Watanabe2 142dot Inc., Seoul, Republic of Korea 2Language Technologies Institute, Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, USA {hyungyong.kim, byeongyeol.kim, yunkyu.lim, jihwan.park, yooncheol.ju, jinseok.park, youshin.lim, seungwoo.yu, hanbin.lee }@42dot.ai, sjchoi.hmg@gmail.com, shinjiw@ieee.org Abstract Self-training has gained increasing attention due to its no-table performance improvement in speech recognition. How-ever, conventional self-training techniques have two key limi-tations: (1) labeled dataset is required for training a teacher to produce a pseudo-target, and (2) the first teacher trained with the small labeled dataset faces an over-fitting issue, generat-ing noisy pseudo-targets for unseen datasets.\nOur approach adopts an unsupervised automatic speech recognition model as the teacher, thus solely utilizing the unlabeled dataset. As the proposed model also learns phonetic information from the UASR teacher at the intermediate layer, the pseudo-target at the higher layer contains more ASR-related information than that of Data2vec2. Experimental results on the LibriSpeech show that our model outperforms Data2vec2, the state-of-the-art self-supervised learning model, achieving 8.9% and 4.3% relative word error rate reduction on test-clean and test-other.\nIndex Terms: self-training, self-supervised learning, speech recognition 1. Introduction Recent self-supervised learning (SSL) has shown successful re-sults on signal processing fields, e.g., image [1, 2], natural lan-guage [3], and speech signal processing [4]. For speech pro-cessing, there are many successful models, including Wav2vec2 [4], HuBERT [5], W2v-BERT [6], Data2vec [7], and Data2vec2 [8]. The SSL models are based on transformer architecture [9], however different pseudo-targets and losses are utilized to pre-train the model with a speech-only database. In order to com-prehend the progressive development of SSL models for ASR, what kinds of information is included in pseudo-targets is the most important question.\nWav2vec2 generates positive and negative pseudo-targets by discretizing its convolutional outputs.\nIt optimizes con-trastive loss to closely align predicted embeddings with pos-itive targets and distance them from negatives.\nAs the tar-gets in Wav2vec2 are continuously updated without explicit constraints, identifying the information contained within these targets becomes challenging.\nIn contrast to Wav2vec2, Hu-BERT [5] learns a more explicit informed target that clusters mel-frequency cepstral coefficient (MFCC) features to describe phone-related information. For a low-resourced setup for SSL ASR benchmark, HuBERT shows better performance than that of Wav2vec2 [5].\nContrary to SSL methods, self-training for ASR, a task-specific semi-supervised learning approach, makes the targets include the most explicit information, i.e. pseudo-text label.\nAn initial ASR model is built with a small amount of labeled data, which can produce a pseudo-label from a large amount of unlabeled data. Subsequent models are trained on these pseudo-labels to extract better pseudo-labels. The same process keeps iterating until the performance improvement is saturated. Com-monly, due to the ASR-friendly targets, a self-training method generally overcomes the SSL model for ASR tasks [10].\nAlthough the self-training method shows the best per-formance in ASR, the performance is highly dependent on the teacher models producing pseudo-targets. When the first teacher is trained with a small amount of data, it makes inac-curate and noisy pseudo labels from a large number of unla-beled speech datasets [11]. Since the second teacher is already trained with unlabeled data, it can produce better quality pseudo labels, thereby significantly enhancing the performance at the second iteration compared to that of the first iteration in self-training [10, 12]. It is a critical problem for self-training that needs multi-stage training, which causes a lot of training costs compared to the SSL model.\nIn this paper, we propose a new self-training method to overcome the over-fitting problem. In order to remove the lim-itation of the first teacher in self-training, we train an unsuper-vised automatic speech recognition (UASR) model [13, 14, 15] as the first teacher, which can be trained by unpaired speech and text data. As the UASR model has fluent phonetic infor-mation, we apply phonetic supervision loss on the intermediate layer of Data2vec2 [8], the state-of-the-art (SOTA) SSL model, which results in learning phonetic information in lower layers and phonetically-guided contextualized information in higher layers. Our approach is motivated by [11, 16, 17] that ASR model sequentially converts speech into phonetic, linguistic in-formation, and text. In addition, these representations can be progressively learned by auxiliary intermediate loss [18, 19].\nIn our experiments, we implemented comparison studies to verify the effectiveness of the intermediate loss and superiority of explicit pseudo-targets. Finally, for a small amount of la-beled data setting for SSL, we showed the SOTA performance compared to the conventional SSL and self-training methods.\nTo the best of our knowledge, this is the first successful attempt to achieve the SOTA results using the UASR teacher model.\n2. Backgrounds 2.1. Self-supervised Learning: Data2vec2 Data2vec2 trains a transformer encoder with a self-distillation strategy, in which a student and teacher are kept updated. The student takes speech X as an input and converts to latent speech representation Z = [z1, z2, · · · , zT ] by a multi-layer convolu-tional encoder where T is the number of speech frames. The latent representation Z is randomly masked and fed to the trans-former layer to learn local and global relationships among the speech frames by self-attention algorithm, which outputs a con-Interspeech 2024 1-5 September 2024, Kos, Greece 2865 10.21437/Interspeech.2024-2323 text representation C = [c1, c2, · · · , cT ]. In order to predict a pseudo-target yt on the masked frames, a final decoder projects the context representation C to ft(X).\nFor the pseudo target yt, Data2vec2 produces a contextu-alized target from features of the teacher’s transformer layers to include not just local but global relationships among speech frames. Since unstable training or even mode collapse [1] fre-quently occurs when prediction and target are from the same architecture [1, 2, 20], Data2vec2 uses exponential moving av-erage (EMA) to make the parameters of the teacher model up-dated slowly. The EMA formulation is as follows ∆←τ∆+ (1 −τ)θ (1) where ∆is the EMA network as the teacher to produce the tar-gets, θ is the prediction network as the student, and τ controls an update ratio of each parameter. For utilizing information of multiple layers, Data2vec2 chooses the top K layers of L trans-former blocks and averages them to make the targets as yt = 1 K XL l=L−K+1 ˆ at l (2) where ˆ at l is transformer’s output and l is the layer index.\nThe student is updated to minimize mean square error (MSE) loss between the prediction and pseudo-targets from the EMA teacher on masked frames. The MSE loss functions are fol-lowed as LSSL (yt, ft (X)) = (yt −ft (X))2 (3) 2.2. Unsupervised Speech Recognition: Wav2vec-u2 Recently, Unsupervised ASR (UASR) has been proposed to train the ASR model with unpaired speech and text data [21, 22]. Contrary to previous studies on UASR [13, 14, 15], Wav2vec-u families utilizes the contextualized representation C of the pre-trained SSL model as an input to produce phoneme sequences and showed promising ASR results, which is possi-ble by phonetic information in Wav2vec2.\nWav2vec-u2 is structured with two primary components: a generator G that produces phoneme sequences G(C) as fake samples, and a discriminator D to differentiate the fake se-quences G(C) from real samples P r that is phoneme sequences obtained from text data via an external phonemizer. By adver-sarial training process, G and D are alternatively trained to min-imize their respective loss functions. The loss functions with auxiliary loss terms are as follows min G max D EP r [log D(P r)] −EC [log(1 −D(G(C)))] −λLgp + γLsp + ηLpd (4) The first two terms are loss function for adversarial training [23]. The third term is the gradient penalty on D for better con-vergence [24], the fourth term is the smoothness penalty on G to penalize locally inconsistent phone prediction [21], and the last term is phoneme diversity loss on G to encourage a diverse output over the phone set [21] where λ, γ, and η are the weights for each term. Since we could not observe the performance dif-ference by a auxiliary self-supervised loss Lss in Wav2vec-u2 [21], we did not use Lss.\nPre-training Fine-tuning Pre-training Fine-tuning Feature-based Self-training[11,12] Proposed Method Text-based Self-training[10,25] GAN Training Figure 1: Training process of self-training methods. U and S are unsupervised and supervised datasets. Mtea and Mstu are teacher and student model.\n3. Proposed Method 3.1. UASR Teacher-guided Self-training As shown in Figure 1, we describe the training process of con-ventional and proposed self-training methods. There are two kinds of conventional self-training methods for ASR, a text-based self-training [10, 25] producing pseudo text transcription and a feature-based self-training [11, 12] making pseudo-label from features of the network. In the first fine-tuning, the con-ventional methods should be trained with the supervised dataset to make the first teacher Mtea(S). When the supervised dataset S is much smaller compared to the amounts of unlabeled data U, it results in an over-fitting problem for the first teacher model Mtea(S) or noisy labels for unseen data [11]. In order to solve the shortage of the supervised dataset, our method trains the first teacher Mtea(U) with the unpaired speech and text data, by adversarial training of UASR [13, 14].\n3.2. Phonetic Supervision on Intermediate Layer Since conventional distillation has an inborn limitation that the performance of the student is highly dependent on a fixed teacher network [26, 27], self-distillation is recently proposed to solve the limitation, which makes the teacher keep updat-ing [1, 7, 8, 28]. As shown in Figure 2, our method also applies self-distillation based on Data2vec2 [8]. Data2vec2 produced the contextualized targets yt, however, it is unknown what kinds of information are included in yt. Our method applies pho-netic supervision of UASR teacher on the intermediate layer of Data2vec2, which makes Data2vec2 produce more complex contextualized targets based on explicit phonetic information that is closely related to ASR downstream tasks. Specifically, the intermediate target ylow t is extracted from the intermedi-ate features of the generator including fluent phonetic informa-tion. At the L-th layer, the output of transformer in the student network is projected to f low t (X) by the intermediate decoder.\nThe model minimized MSE loss between ylow t and f low t (X) on masked frames, which is as follows: Ldistill \u0010 ylow t , f low t (X) \u0011 = \u0010 ylow t −f low t (X) \u00112 (5) In comparison with Data2vec2, the parameters of student are updated by Ldistill as follows θhigh ←θhigh + α · dLSSL dθhigh (6) θlow ←θlow + α · dLSSL dθlow + β · dLdistill dθlow (7) where α and β are learning rates. θhigh has the parameters of the layer upper than L-th layer, and θlow includes L-th layer and below it.\n2866 Speech Conv.\nMasking Z Transformer (Student) L layers Final Decoder Conv.\nPre-trained wav2vec2 (freeze) FCN Conv.\nWav2vec-u2 Data2vec2 MSE Loss Top K layers averaging Transformer (Teacher) K layers Transformer (Teacher) L layers MSE Loss Intemediate Decoder Transformer (Student) K layers Phonetic Supervison Figure 2: Model architecture of the proposed method.\nDue to the intermediate loss Ldistill and the update of stu-dent’s parameters with Equation (1), at L-th layer, the outputs of the teacher transformer have the ability to produce phoneme sequences. Note that we define L-th layer as an information boundary layer for phonetic information, which was critical for performance. The new contextualized targets yt guided by phoneme information are used in Equation (3). The final losses are as follows: Ltotal = LSSL + κ · Ldistill (8) where κ a weighting value for Ldistill.\n4. Experimental Settings 4.1. Database We used the LibriSpeech (LS) dataset for unsupervised pre-training, specifically the LS 960 hours including train-clean-100, train-clean-360, and train-other-500. For supervised fine-tuning, we used the LS 100 hours (train-clean-100). We vali-dated the models on LS development sets (dev-clean, dev-other) and evaluated them on LS test sets (test-clean, test-other).\n4.2. Training UASR Teacher For generative teachers, we trained wav2vec-u2 with LS speech dataset and the LibriSpeech-Language Model (LS-LM) cor-pus1. We followed the configuration from Wav2vec-u2 [22] and used the checkpoint of pre-trained Wav2vec2 Base [4] from Fairseq [29]. We used g2p-en phonemizer [30] to con-vert unpaired text to phoneme sequences. Then, we randomly put a silence token between the phoneme sequences with 50% probability to represent silence in speech [22]. The architec-tures of the generator and discriminator are the same as that of Wav2vec-u2. Since GAN training commonly suffers from unstable training, Wav2vec-u2 sometimes failed the training 1http://www.openslr.org/11/ Teacher Loss DB for teacher test-clean test-other CTC-finetuned Ldistill Paired LS100 4.3 9.4 CTC-finetuned Ldistill Paired LS960 3.7 8.6 W2v-u2 Ldistill Unpaired LS960 5.1 11.3 W2v-u2(MTL) LSSL + κ · Ldistill Unpaired LS960 4.7 9.5 W2v-u2(interm.) LSSL + κ · Ldistill Unpaired LS960 4.1 8.9 Table 1: Comparison study of different losses.\nInterm. Teacher DB for teacher test-clean test-other None None 4.5 9.3 Contrastive None 4.7 9.6 CTC-finetuned Paired LS960 4.2 9.0 W2v-u2 Unpaired LS960 4.1 8.9 Table 2: Comparison study of different information types.\n[21, 22], which we also observed similar results. So, we trained the model 10 times and selected the best model for the teacher, which got a phone error rate 21.54% on the dev-other dataset processed with voice activity detection. For supervised teach-ers, we used the checkpoint of CTC-finetuned Wav2vec2 from Fairseq. For choosing λ, γ, and η in Equation 4, we followed the same policy of Wav2vec-u2.\n4.3. Pre-training and Fine-tuning The proposed model had the same configuration as the Data2vec2 BASE model [7], consisting of a CNN-based wave-form encoder with a downsampling rate of 320, 12 transformer layers, and a convolutional decoder layer. We used Tesla V100 16 GPUs with 32GB for all pre-training stages where a batch for one GPU includes at most 62.5 seconds of speech. The pre-training steps were 400k. The training hyper-parameters are the exactly same as Data2vec2 [8].\nThe intermediate decoder has the same architecture and padding rules as the final decoder.\nThe intermediate targets from Wav2vec-u2 were also normalized by instance normal-ization in Data2vec2. We experimentally selected κ = 0.1 in Equation 8. For a fair comparison with Data2vec2, we selected the intermediate layer as the 4th layer.\nFor the LS 100h dataset, we fine-tuned the pre-training model with CTC loss, which followed the same regime and con-figuration of Wav2vec2 [4]. Since we used V100 8 GPUs with 32GB for fine-tuning, the batch size is reduced to 1,600K due to out-of-memory. We selected the best model by WER result on LS dev-other.\n5. Experimental Results 5.1. Effectiveness of Intermediate Loss To select the optimal objectives for self-training, we con-ducted an ablation study involving variations in the teacher model and loss functions. In Table 1, “CTC-finetuned” teacher corresponded to the fine-tuned Wav2vec2 utilizing the paired dataset, while “Wav2vec-u2” referred to the base configura-tion of Wav2vec-u2 trained with the unpaired LS960h dataset and LS-LM corpus [22]. When employing Wav2vec-u2 as the teacher, we explored three different settings: (1) only the dis-tillation loss for the final layer was employed, (2) multi-task learning (MTL) for the final layer, combined with the original SSL loss, and (3) incorporating the proposed distillation loss into the intermediate layer with SSL loss for the final.\nAs shown in Table 1, in the case of the CTC-finetuned 2867 teacher model, we observed a significant performance improve-ment when the teacher model was trained with a larger dataset.\nThis strongly implies the presence of over-fitting and noisy la-bel issues within the self-training process.\nFurthermore, we conducted a comprehensive comparison of three approaches utilizing Ldistill: single distillation, MTL, and the intermediate loss strategy. When training the model solely with the distillation loss, the self-training heavily relied on the teacher model and thus did not yield satisfactory results.\nHowever, a significant breakthrough was achieved by combin-ing distillation with SSL loss, yielding promising results even in the absence of any paired dataset for self-training. The best performance was achieved in the case of applying Ldistill at the intermediate layer. It outperformed the conventional self-training approach that utilized the fine-tuned teacher model with the paired LS 100h dataset. Based on these findings, we chose the intermediate method as our primary objective.\n5.2. Explicitness of Pseudo-targets To verify the impact of target information, we conducted an ab-lation study by distilling various types of information into the intermediate layer. Since we previously confirmed in Section 5.1 that applying the generative teacher at the intermediate layer yielded the best performance, we employed this approach as our baseline. In Table 2, the first row presents the results of Data2vec2, which was the backbone SSL model. While main-taining the model’s architecture and objectives unchanged, we employed different targets for the intermediate layer.\nThe contrastive teacher was similar to the W2v-BERT framework [6], in which the same discrete target is utilized for the contrastive loss on the intermediate layer and the MLM loss on the final layer. We applied the contrastive loss on the 4th layer but utilized LSSL in Equation (3) for the last layer.\nUnlike the performance improvement observed in W2v-BERT, where the same informed targets were employed across differ-ent losses, the performance of contrastive loss combined with LSSL was degraded compared to the Data2vec2. This suggests that the intermediate loss should be carefully applied as the aux-iliary loss when using different informed targets.\nAs shown in Table 2, the models distilled from CTC-finetuned and Wav2vec-u2 teachers, self-training methods, achieved better results than SSL methods. This indicates that these teachers were able to offer more supportive targets for training ASR, including phonetic and linguistic information. In-terestingly, the student distilled from the Wav2vec-u2 teacher showed comparable results compared to the scenario where the CTC-finetuned teacher was used for distillation. Even with-out requiring any paired dataset, we showed that the generative teacher could be an effective teacher for self-training.\n5.3. Low-resource Speech Recognition Table 3 shows the WER results for low-resource labeled data sets, where LS 960h and LS 100h were used for the pre-training and fine-tuning stages, respectively.\nWe compared the pro-posed method with the recent SSL and self-training models, in-cluding Wav2vec2 [4], HuBERT [5], WavLM [32], Data2vec2 [8], MonoBERT [33], PolyBERT [33], CTC-clustering [12], PBERT [12], and ASBERT [11]. In order to demonstrate the ef-fects of unpaired speech and text data, we focused on the WER results with CTC greedy decoding without a language model (LM).\nAmong the SSL methods, Data2vec2 is currently the SOTA algorithm for ASR. We reported the results of Data2vec2 by LS960 (pre-training) - LS100 (fine-tuning) Model Pre-training DB test-clean test-other Self-supervised learning Wav2vec2 [31] Speech-only LS960 6.1 13.5 HuBERT [31] Speech-only LS960 6.3 13.2 WavLM [32] Speech-only LS960 5.7 12.0 Data2vec2 Speech-only LS960 4.5 9.3 Self-training methods MonoBERT [33] Unpaired LS960 5.5 11.7 PolyBERT [33] Unpaired LS960 4.9 11.1 CTC-clustering [12] Paired LS100 5.2 11.4 PBERT [12] Paired LS100 4.2 9.5 ASBERT [11] Paired LS100 4.4 9.9 Ours, CTC-finetuned teacher Paired LS960 4.2 9.0 Ours, Wav2vec-u2 teacher Unpaired LS960 4.1 8.9 Table 3: WER results for low-resource labeled data. Decoding results without LM are reported.\nfine-tuning the pre-trained checkpoint from the Fairseq toolkit [29]. For a fair comparison, Data2vec2 and our methods were fine-tuned using the same experimental configuration in section 4.3. In a comparison with Data2vec2, the proposed method achieved a relative word error rate reduction (RERR) of 8.9% on the test-clean dataset and 4.3% on the test-other dataset, respectively.\nWe concluded that the proposed phonetic su-pervision on intermediate layer help Data2vec2 produce better pseudo-targets for ASR, so that the proposed methods surpass Data2vec2.\nIn comparison with self-training methods, such as CTC-clustering, PBERT, and ASBERT, our methods showed the best performance results by effectively leveraging unpaired audio and text data.\nIt is important to note that the existing self-training methods employed LS 960h audio data for pre-training and LS 100h transcriptions for teacher training, while our pro-posed method was solely trained using unpaired data during the pre-training stage. Without relying on the paired dataset during the pre-training, our framework could train a support-ive teacher model for ASR, consequently achieving better WER performance.\nVery recently, MonoBERT and PolyBERT use Wav2vec-u2 model to enhance the target of HuBERT on the final layer.\nHowever, in the context of knowledge distillation, the teacher’s performance serves as an upper limit for the student’s perfor-mance. Considering that the performance of Wav2vec-u2 was noticeably worse than that of the supervised ASR model as the teacher, the performances of MonoBERT and PolyBERT fell behind the SOTA for ASR in Table 3. As the proposed method applied the phonetic supervision by Wav2vec-u2 on the inter-mediate layer, it showed the SOTA performance.\n6. Conclusions In this paper, we proposed a new self-training scheme using only unpaired speech and text data. In order to solve the prob-lem of over-fitting and noisy labels for the teacher in self-training, the UASR model was utilized as the teacher. The abla-tion study showed the effectiveness of intermediate supervision with phonetic information. From the experimental results on the LS benchmark, our proposed self-training approach achieved superior performance compared to both the conventional SSL method and other self-training techniques.\n2868 7. References [1] J. B. Grill, F. Strub, F. Altch´ e, C. Tallec, P. H. Richemond, E. Buchatskaya, C. Doersch, B. A. Pires, Z. D. Guo, M. G. Azar, B. Piot, K. Kavukcuoglu, R. Munos, and M. Valko, “Bootstrap your own latent: A new approach to self-supervised learning.” in Proc. NeurIPS., 2020, p. 21271–21284.\n[2] X. Chen and K. He, “Exploring simple siamese representation learning.” in Proc. CVPR., 2021, pp. 15 750–15 758.\n[3] J. Devlin, M. W. Chang, K. Lee, and K. Toutanova, “Bert: Pre-training of deep bidirectional transformers for language under-standing.” 